<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-503-131  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 503 131.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 9 1990 v4 n34 p31(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New profit-sharing plan starts at Apple.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Norr, Henry.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (personnel management).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Topic:     Profit SharingEmployee BenefitsEmployee RelationsComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Cupertino, Calif.andP;  -- Version 2.0.1 of Apple's employee profit-sharing planwent into effect last week.andP;  The new formula is a revised version of one thatprovoked sharp controversy among employees when it was first announced earlythis year.andM;Unlike the previous formula, which was tied solely to operating profits, thenew one bases payouts on both profits and growth in revenues.andP;  To provide anadditional incentive, the plan also sets a growth threshold: No payments willbe made in quarters when growth falls below 5 percent.andM;CEO John Sculley originally proposed a 10 percent threshold when Apple beganmodifying its previous plan early this year, but the company backed off whensome employees, citing fat bonuses recently awarded to top executives,denounced the plan as a disguised pay cut.andM;According to a report in the San Jose Mercury News last week, the old formulayielded a payout equal to 12.7 percent of each employee's salary in the firstquarter of fiscal 1990, while the new plan would have produced a payout of8.3 percent.andP;  If quarterly sales grow by more than 15 percent, however,payouts under the new plan will exceed those possible under the old terms.andM;Apple's plan apparently remains more generous than those of most of itscompetitors.andP;  According to the Mercury News, a survey carried out last yearby Radford Associates, a San Jose compensation consulting company, found thatthe average payment among companies in the computer industry withprofit-sharing plans amounted to 4.6 percent of base pay.andO;</TEXT></DOC>